{
  "answer": "In Charles Comte's *Traité de Législation Vol III*, Chapter 33 (\"Of the relations observed between the military aristocracy and the industrious class, among the peoples of the Caucasian species of northwest Africa\") presents the central claim that Egyptian society under Mamluk and Turkish rule is rigidly divided into a small, organized military aristocracy that monopolizes power and property by right of conquest, treating the large, unorganized industrious class as a mere \"passive instrument\" for its enjoyments.[^1][^2]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation Vol III*, [p-f00fbb](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iii-ca589a/33/translation/#p-f00fbb).\n[^2]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation Vol III*, [p-0e7e56](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iii-ca589a/33/translation/#p-0e7e56).",
